http.title: Internet Scanning Service Explained
http.html:
Greetings, stranger! You have encountered a friendly bot 🥳

What is internet scanning?

Internet scanning, at its core, is the act of probing the entire or a portion of the internet to collect information about devices, servers, and services that are publicly accessible. Think of it as a "Google for devices" – while search engines like Google index web pages, services like Shodan and Censys index device metadata.

Internet scanning from a web security perspective

There are several reasons why benign internet scanning, such as the scanning observed from this IP-address, is contributing to a more secure internet:

  • Asset Discovery: Organizations can use these services to find out if they have any unprotected assets facing the internet. It's not uncommon for large companies to be unaware of all their internet-facing devices.
  • Vulnerability Awareness: Scanning services can highlight known vulnerabilities in devices or software versions. This can be crucial for timely patching and defense.
  • Research & Analysis: Cybersecurity researchers often utilize such services to get a sense of the global threat landscape, analyze trends, and develop protective measures.
  • Incident Response: If there's a significant global vulnerability or a new attack type, scanning can provide insights into affected devices and their distribution.

It can be hard to discern harmless scanning like this from malicious scanning conducted by cybercriminals, but there are some key differences:

  • Anonymization: Malicious actors often use web anonymization services such as Tor or VPNs to conceal their identity and location, making it harder to trace back and attribute the scanning activity.
  • Frequency of packets: Malicious actors will typically send thousands or even millions of packets against your systems because their scanning is targeted and aggressive. In contrast, our scanning is passive and widespread, focusing on a broader internet-wide view rather than specific targets.
  • TCP connections: On its own, simple SYN-scanning like the one you observed from this IP address doesn't offer much value to attackers. Attackers will mainly be interested in garnering details about operating systems, services, and potential vulnerabilities. To achieve this, they must establish full TCP connections. You will never see a TCP connection from our scanning infrastructure.

Addressing the activity you have observed from this IP

SYN scanning, often known as "half-open" or "stealth" scanning, is a method used to identify only if a specific port on a device is open or closed. Here's a simplified breakdown:

  1. Our scanner sends a SYN (synchronize) packet to a target device's specific port.
  2. If the port is open, the target device sends back a SYN-ACK (synchronize-acknowledge) packet.
  3. Our scanner then sends an RST (reset) packet to terminate the connection or simply doesn't respond.

This process is considered harmless because:

  • No Full Connection: SYN scanning doesn't establish a full TCP connection. Since it's terminated before completion, it generally doesn't log or trigger many conventional intrusion detection systems.
  • Minimal Resources: SYN scans use minimal target system resources, so they will not cause any disruptions or slow-downs. On top of this, we randomize the target selection by scrambling the entire IPv4 address space. This is to ensure that the packets from us are as few and far from each other as possible.
  • Purely Informational: The scan merely determines if a port is open or closed. No data is extracted from the device or altered in any manner.

Opting out

If you don't want your IP addresses to be scanned, or if you have any concerns, you can reach out directly to {webscout.abusecontact} and we will exclude your infrastructure from the scanning activity. As a general rule, if you don’t want to have a service probed, it should not be exposed to the internet in the first place.

While combating all internet scanners will be a losing battle, the Danish Energy CERT have compiled a list of ranges belonging to known internet scanners which you can feed into your web application firewall. The list is available here.

CVE-2021-23017.summary: A security issue in nginx resolver was identified, which might allow an attacker who is able to forge UDP packets from the DNS server to cause 1-byte memory overwrite, resulting in worker process crash or potential other impact.

CVE-2021-3618.summary: ALPACA is an application layer protocol content confusion attack, exploiting TLS servers implementing different protocols but using compatible certificates, such as multi-domain or wildcard certificates. A MiTM attacker having access to victim's traffic at the TCP/IP layer can redirect traffic from one subdomain to another, resulting in a valid TLS session. This breaks the authentication of TLS and cross-protocol attacks may be possible where the behavior of one protocol service may compromise the other at the application layer.
